node.text:
With the opening of our newest flagship in Hawaii, it was important for us to pay homage to the community we are joining. It is always our intention to respect the cultures of our new homes and get to know some of the local businesses that came before us. In Honolulu, we had the pleasure of connecting with three businesses that welcomed us with open arms and introduced us to the services they’ve been providing Hawaiians for years. After learning more about them, we felt inspired to support them and their craft, which is why it was our honor to provide each business with a $10,000 grant and a platform to share their stories.

Kākoʻo ʻŌiwi - a community-based non-profit organization whose farm has produced over 50,000 pounds of sustainable native crops, and leads an ongoing agricultural restoration project that promotes social and economic advancement for local businesses and individuals.

Kamaka Ukulele - a ukulele factory that started as a one-man shop and has now been in business for over a century, invented the pineapple ukulele, and continues to be operated by the same family it was founded by. 

Lin’s Lei Shop - one of the most well-regarded lei shops in Hawaii, this family-owned company has been a staple in Honolulu’s beloved Chinatown district for thirty four-years.

We’re grateful for the opportunity to get to know these businesses and look forward to fostering more relationships in our new home in the years to come.

Music by: @thegreen808
“Recipe”

node.text:
In February of last year, we were honored to receive a message from @thehouseofmandela about working together on a project to spread awareness of the Mandela Freedom Project, Mandela Day, and to honor the legacy of Nelson Mandela. We had the fortune of working directly with Nelson Mandela’s daughter Makaziwe Mandela, his granddaughter Tukwini Mandela, and the House of Mandela to design a special capsule collection, as well as host volunteer and donation initiatives that align with the family’s values.

Mandela Day is a global call to action that celebrates the idea that each individual has the power to transform the world and the ability to make an impact. It is not meant to be a public holiday, but as a day to uphold the legacy of Nelson Mandela and his values through volunteering and community service. Mandela fought for social justice for 67 years, we’re asking you to start with 67 minutes.

We sat down with Nelson Mandela’s grandson @kwekumandela to discuss how his grandfather impacted him and his family’s life and purpose, his perspective on today’s current landscape, Mandela Day, and more.

This Monday we will launch a capsule with the House of Mandela where proceeds will be donated to different organizations that align with the Six Pillars of Mandela. These include #HashtagLunchBag, Black Girls CODE, and The Innocence Project.

node.text:
To celebrate the holiday, we’ve partnered with the Martin Luther King Jr. Estate and his son Martin Luther King III to pay tribute to Dr. King and continue to spread the message of his vision. 

Kith’s own @marlonbeck2 had a conversation with @officialmlking3 at Dr. King’s childhood home and church in Atlanta to talk about how the youth can continue the pursuit of change in America.

This Monday we will launch a capsule with the MLK Jr. Estate where 100% of the proceeds will be donated. 50% will go to @officialmlking3’s foundation, the Drum Major Institute. The other 50% will be evenly distributed to the Youth Direct Action Fund, March for Our Lives, Do Something, and the Alliance for Youth Action.

Directed by @rayneutron

node.text:
With the opening of our newest flagship in Hawaii, it was important for us to pay homage to the community we are joining. It is always our intention to respect the cultures of our new homes and get to know some of the local businesses that came before us. In Honolulu, we had the pleasure of connecting with three businesses that welcomed us with open arms and introduced us to the services they’ve been providing Hawaiians for years. After learning more about them, we felt inspired to support them and their craft, which is why it was our honor to provide each business with a $10,000 grant and a platform to share their stories.

Kākoʻo ʻŌiwi - a community-based non-profit organization whose farm has produced over 50,000 pounds of sustainable native crops, and leads an ongoing agricultural restoration project that promotes social and economic advancement for local businesses and individuals.

Kamaka Ukulele - a ukulele factory that started as a one-man shop and has now been in business for over a century, invented the pineapple ukulele, and continues to be operated by the same family it was founded by. 

Lin’s Lei Shop - one of the most well-regarded lei shops in Hawaii, this family-owned company has been a staple in Honolulu’s beloved Chinatown district for thirty four-years.

We’re grateful for the opportunity to get to know these businesses and look forward to fostering more relationships in our new home in the years to come.

We are proud to present our newest Kith flagship store in Hawaii. Located at 2301 Kalakaua Avenue in Honolulu. 

After opening a pop-up in Hawaii in 2019, we fell in love with the local culture and community. Shortly after we began working on creating a permanent space so that we could offer a holistic Kith experience to Honolulu. 

Our core design aesthetics have been channeled through a Hawaiian lens to create our two-floor flagship. This store will offer our Kith mens, women’s and kid’s collections, in addition to multi-brand footwear and accessories. It also includes a Kith Treats cereal-and-ice cream parlor that offers our full menu. 

Doors open tomorrow morning at 9AM. This weekend our hours will be 9AM-9PM. After Sunday our daily hours will be 10AM-9PM. 

We cannot wait to meet our new Hawaii community and share this space together.

node.text:
We are honored to have worked directly with Nelson Mandela’s daughter Makaziwe Mandela, his granddaughter Tukwini Mandela, and the House of Mandela to help spread the message of Mandela Day and create this capsule. Through this collaborative process with our design team, Maki & Tukwini created the Kith for Mandela Day 2021 apparel capsule that releases tomorrow at Kith shops, 11AM EST on Kith.com & 11AM CET on EU.Kith.com.

Proceeds from this release will be donated to different organizations that align with the Six Pillars of Mandela. These include #HashtagLunchBag, Black Girls CODE, and the Innocence Project.

#HashtagLunchBag is a volunteer organization that creates and donates bagged lunches that help provide food to local underserved communities.

Black Girls CODE is a nonprofit organization whose mission is to increase the number of women of color in the digital technology space by introducing girls 7-17 to CS.

The Innocence Project is a group of independent organizations that exonerate and support the innocent, and redress the cases of wrongful conviction.
